03986nam a22005535i 9780822398998DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19981998ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223989987 a10.1515/97808223989982doi  a(DE-B1597)554399  a(OCoLC)1229161171  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aTR23b.D38 1998 7aPHO0140002bisacsh04a770/.822211 aDavidov, Judith Fryer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen's Camera Work :bSelf/Body/Other in American Visual Culture /cJudith Fryer Davidov. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (512 p.) :b220 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tI Histories : Versions and Subversions -- tII The Geometry of Bodies: Gender and Genre in Pictorialist Photography -- tIII "Always the Navajo Took the Picture" -- tIV Containment and Excess: Representing African Americans -- tV "The Only Gentile among the Jews": Dorothea Lange's Documentary Photography -- tVI The Body's Geography: Female Versions of Landscape -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen's Camera Work explores how photographs have been and are used to construct versions of history and examines how photographic representations of otherness often tell stories about the self. In the process, Judith Fryer Davidov focuses on the lives and work of a particular network of artists linked by time, interaction, influence, and friendship-one that included Gertrude Käsebier, Imogen Cunningham, Dorothea Lange, and Laura Gilpin.Women's Camera Work ranges from American women's photographic practices during the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries to a study of landscape photography. Using contemporary cultural studies discourse to critique influential male-centered historiography and the male-dominated art world, Davidov exhibits the work of these women; tells their absorbing stories; and discusses representations of North American Indians, African Americans, Asian Americans, and the migrant poor. Evaluating these photographers' distinct contributions to constructions of Americanness and otherness, she helps us to discover the power of reading images closely, and to learn to see through these women's eyes.In presenting one of the most important strands of American photography, this richly illustrated book will interest students of American visual culture, women's studies, and general readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aPhotographyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen photographerszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPhotography / Photoessays & Documentaries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398998zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398998.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles